I will trade 500 rounds of 5.56 for 1000 rounds of 7.62x39.

--------------------------------------------------------

--If we both use non-inflated prices (before inflation) ammo ran about $0.40 to $0.45 per round for 5.56 and about $0.20 to $0.25 per round for 7.62x39.  That means we could trade 2 rounds of 5.56 per one round of 7.62x39.

title: For Sale:  CZ99, CZ999, EZ9 handgun Zastava Arms
postcontent:
For sale:  new CZ 99 (CZ999, EZ9) handgun pistol caliber 40 S&W, Century International Arms, Zastava Arms Serbia (Yugoslavia). Price $799.
Magazine capacity 11+1 rounds (with the extended mags 15 and 20 rounds). Mags from Beretta 92 fit as well.
In original box, never fired, brand new. Comes with cleaning brush, manual, warranty, factory certificate of pressure testing and quality control.
This is the best handgun in the world (my opinion). A  40 S&W caliber is the best choice between the stopping power, number of rounds in the mag and the price. This is the caliber that is being used by US police, secret service and special units.
CZ 99 reassembles Sig Sauer P226, but in many ways is better and more improved then Sig. It's combat-proven all over the world, and it is the service weapon of choice for the police and military forces in many countries.
I had a CZ 99 in the military and police service and as my personal concealed carry weapon for many years. My experience is 100% positive. There was not one malfunction on any of these guns that I know of. They performed flawlessly under any condition and without cleaning, for months of extensive use, and accuracy was always the same.
The feeling and fit of the CZ 99 in your hands, while aiming and shooting, can be compared with the Mercedes amongst cars. And yes, I have been shooting many different guns and calibers for the past 25 years.  I own a Beretta 92 and a Sig Sauer as well, and have been shooting and comparing them side by side millions of times. My choice is always CZ 99. My hands are small to medium size, and it fits well.

In America, CZ 99 is known under different names and was imported by different companies:

CZ 99, CZ 99S, CZ 999, CZ999 Scorpion, ZDA, EZ9, EZ40, CZ05, Zastava Arms, Serbia Yugoslavia.
US importers: Nationwide sports, TD Arms, Century International Arms, Charles Daly ZDA, Arsenal, EAA.
License: KSN Industries Israel - Golan, Tressitu South Africa.
"CZ" is short for Crvena Zastava, translates to Red Flag, which is the old name of the factory from Kragujevac, Serbia. This Factory started making canons and firearms in 1800s. With the rich history and recognizable quality has set their reputation. Today they make many good quality firearms, handguns, hunting rifles, shotguns, military firearms, machine guns... including the famous AK 47s, which are practically indestructible and the most reliable in the whole world, same as CZ 99. We had these AKs and CZs falling from the chopper from 200 yards and, they worked like new afterwards.

The CZ 99 is a military-police service gun, or it can be a very dependable self defense and concealed carry gun. Alloy frame and polymer grips make it very light.

Parts exposed to high dynamic loads such as hammer, firing pin and unlocking insert (locking block) are made of the military ordnance steel
Hard-chromed barrel inside and out, no need for oiling, will never corrode. Barrel length 4,5", machined slide from one solid block of steel, full length slider rails.
Forged alloy frame, decocker and slide release in one, ambidextrous.
Good trigger SA and DA (single & double action), low recoil, firing pin block, easy field strip.
Barrel is made from same material used in the M-84 machine gun and is hard-chromed. In the test done in the USA in 1991 it was found that it dissipated heat very well. While this is not a concern with handguns nearly as much as it is with the machine guns, the ability to dissipate heat rapidly makes the barrel capable of lasting longer due to a shorter expansion/contraction cycle. After many Serbian and FBI tests (mud, water, sand, snow, ice, hot) firing 200,000 rounds from the single gun, there was not one malfunction, and accuracy was the same like the new one. 
It's been accepted like a service weapon for many different police stations in the US.
Not many people here know how good this gun is, because is not advertised globally and many after seeing it, think it's Sig Sauer. To add to that, Sig besides CZ 99, is the only official police service weapon today for many police stations in the US (in 40 S&W caliber only), replacing Beretta 92 and Glock. Portage police station is one of them.

Now is the smart and best time to invest in a good quality affordable hand gun like CZ 99. The time is coming soon when you will not be able to purchase it. Import is very limited and can stop for good. Current owners know how good it is and will never sell it.
This one will go fast. So please no negotiations. Price is firm, $799.
This is private sale. I am not a gun store or a gun dealer. There is no background check, and according to Indiana law, the sale is simple and straightforward - exchanging cash and guns between hands. But, my moral obligation is to make sure that these guns end up in criminal- free and responsible hands. So please, if you can legally own guns you are welcome; if you cannot or have mental issues, you are not welcome, and I will refuse to sell to you.


Contact phone: REDACTED
Location: US Hwy 6, Portage Indiana

title: For Sale:  O.F. Mossberg & sons, Inc. 44us (d) 22 LR PAT
postcontent:
Make: O.F. Mossberg & Sons

Model: Model 44 U.S.

Made: 1931-1932

Barrel Length: 13/16" heavy-type, 26" long with crowned muzzle. 

Sights / Optics: The gun is mounted with a very interesting and complex Vintage Weaver Cub scope with exterior adjustments Microclick windage-and-elevation micrometer adjustable rear sight.

Finish Originality: Original, With a Coat of Varnish

Bore Condition: The rifling is present and crisp. There is no visible erosion.

Overall Condition: This gun retains about 80% of its metal finish. The balance of the finish shows dings and scuffs, as seen in the photographs, none significant. The finish has begun to turn patina under the varnish, though the varnish makes it a bit difficult to asses as the varnish may be giving the patina appearance and may give the barrel a mottled appearance. The Screw heads are used but strong. The markings are present, although a bit difficult to discern under the coat of varnish which has been applied.. Overall, this gun rates in about very good condition.

Mechanics: The action functions smoothly and correctly, although we have not test fired this rifle.

Box & Accessories: None

Our Assessment: Here is one of the best .22 Botl Action Rifles ever made. The barrel is "lead-lapped" which is a process that fills in the micro-cracks in the metal producing a very smooth surface with very little variance or imperfections. It is also very labor intensive and, as a result, expensive. The process is only applied to the most expensive target rifles these days. It was pointed out that it was doing a remarkable job of preserving the wood and metal. This is a rifle which is a significant part of U.S. History, like these used as military training rifles and later sold by the CMP, a reminder of when Americans truly knew how to shoot.

Shoot me an offer and ill consider it. Thanks for looking. Any questions or concerns please call me 1-REDACTED / 1-REDACTED

title: Want To Buy:  Dont Be fooled
postcontent:
Q: What record-keeping procedures should be followed when two private individuals want to engage in a firearms transaction?
When a transaction takes place between private (unlicensed) persons who reside in the same State, the Gun Control Act (GCA) does not require any record keeping. A private person may sell a firearm to another private individual in his or her State of residence and, similarly, a private individual may buy a firearm from another private person who resides in the same State. It is not necessary under Federal law for a Federal firearms licensee (FFL) to assist in the sale or transfer when the buyer and seller are â€œsame-Stateâ€ residents. Of course, the transferor/seller may not knowingly transfer a firearm to someone who falls within any of the categories of prohibited persons contained in the GCA. See 18 U.S.C. Â§Â§ 922(g) and (n). However, as stated above, there are no GCA-required records to be completed by either party to the transfer.

There may be State or local laws or regulations that govern this type of transaction. Contact State Police units or the office of your State Attorney General for information on any such requirements.

Please note that if a private person wants to obtain a firearm from a private person who resides in another State, the firearm will have to be shipped to an FFL in the buyerâ€™s State. The FFL will be responsible for record keeping. See also Question B3.

http://www.atf.gov/firearms/faq/unlicensed-persons.html#shipping-firearms-usps
